comments: Gobert (MIN) firms up over his right foot and establishes himself in Reaves' (LAL) path when he absorbs the body contact during the pick.
James (LAL) extends his left forearm to initiate contact with Towns' (MIN) body after his gather, which knocks him off his path to the basket and affects his driving shot attempt.
Prince (LAL) gives a step of distance when establishing himself in Conley's (MIN) path, and marginal contact occurs during the screen.
Gobert (MIN) rests his forearm on James (LAL), and marginal contact occurs during his drive to the basket.

As James (LAL) brings the ball up toward the basket, incidental contact occurs with Gobert (MIN), who is moving alongside James' path. Contact to an opponent's head/face can be deemed incidental when the result of a natural basketball move, provided the contact is not disproportionate or uncontrolled.
Edwards (MIN) collapses his arms when he absorbs the contact with Reaves (LAL) during the pick.
Gobert (MIN) establishes himself in Reaves' (LAL) path and his legs remain within the frame of his body as contact occurs, which he does not deliver.
Vanderbilt (LAL) makes clean contact with the ball to dislodge it from Gobert (MIN) during the rebound.

Gobert (MIN) grabs and holds Reaves' (LAL) wrist as he tries to step forward to defend Edwards (MIN) on the drive, causing Reaves to lurch awkwardly towards Edwards, exacerbating the contact by Davis (LAL).
Towns (MIN) grabs the rim as he contests the shot, causing the rim and backboard to vibrate, and for the ball to take an unnatural bounce.

As Towns (MIN) begins his dribble, incidental contact occurs with Vanderbilt (LAL) in the backcourt. Contact to an opponent's head/face can be deemed incidental when the result of a natural basketball move, provided the contact is not disproportionate or uncontrolled.
Davis (LAL) has a resting hand on Edwards' (MIN) side, which extends slightly at the end of his drive. The contact is marginal.
James (LAL) does not allow the ball to come to rest during his dribble in the lane.
McDaniels (MIN) does not maintain a legal vertical position as he moves into James' (LAL) body and arm, which alters his driving shot attempt.
All Technical Fouls are reviewed by League Operations.
Gobert (MIN) brings his hands toward Prince (LAL), and marginal contact occurs with his side as Gobert releases away to roll.
Gobert (MIN) goes to, not through, Reaves' (LAL) space, and marginal body contact occurs as the two come together after Gobert releases the pass.
James (LAL) gathers the ball on his left foot and takes two steps before his shot attempt.

James' (LAL) successful shot attempt was initially ruled a two-point shot by on-court referees.  Upon review by the NBA Replay Center Official, there was not clear and conclusive visual evidence that the on-court ruling was incorrect, and therefore no basis to overturn that ruling.  When James raises his heels to jump for his shot, the replay shows his right foot rolling forward so that the toe of his shoe contacts the three-point line.  For a player's shot to be scored a three-point field goal, the player may not touch the three-point line until after his shot is released.
Vanderbilt (LAL) commits a take foul on Edwards (MIN).
